SIMPLE: pull
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pull
<hw>Pull</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pulled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pulling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>pullian</ets>; cf. LG.
<ets>pulen</ets>, and Gael. <ets>peall</ets>, <ets>piol</ets>,
<ets>spiol</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw, or attempt to draw,
toward one; to draw forcibly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ne'er <qex>pull</qex> your hat upon your brows.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He put forth his hand . . . and <qex>pulled</qex> her in.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. viii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw apart; to tear; to rend.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He hath turned aside my ways, and <qex>pulled</qex> me in pieces;
he hath made me desolate.</q> <rj><qau>Lam. iii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To gather with the hand, or by drawing toward one;
to pluck; <as>as, to <ex>pull</ex> fruit; to <ex>pull</ex> flax; to
<ex>pull</ex> a finch.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To move or operate by the motion of drawing towards
one; <as>as, to <ex>pull</ex> a bell; to <ex>pull</ex> an
oar.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Horse Racing)</fld> <def>To hold back, and so
prevent from winning; <as>as, the favorite was
<ex>pulled</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>To take or make, as a proof or
impression; -- hand presses being worked by pulling a lever.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>To strike the ball in a
particular manner. See <er>Pull</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 8.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Never <qex>pull</qex> a straight fast ball to leg.</q> <rj><qau>R.
H. Lyttelton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To pull and haul</b></col>, <cd>to draw hither and
thither.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧ Both are equally <xex>pulled and hauled</xex> to
do that which they are unable to do. ⟦rdquo⟧ <au>South.</au> --
<col><b>To pull down</b></col>, <cd>to demolish; to destroy; to degrade;
<as>as, <ex>to pull down</ex> a house</as>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧ In political
affairs, as well as mechanical, it is easier <xex>to pull down</xex>
than build up.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Howell.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧ To raise the wretched,
and <xex>pull down</xex> the proud.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Roscommon.</au> --
<col><b>To pull a finch</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Finch</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>To pull off</b></col>, <cd>take or draw off.</cd><-- (b) to
perform (esp. something illegal or unethical); as, to pull off a heist
[robbery]. (c) to accomplish, against the odds.--></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1161 --></p>

<p><ent>Pull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pull
<hw>Pull</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To exert one's self in
an act or motion of drawing or hauling; to tug; <as>as, to <ex>pull</ex>
at a rope</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To pull apart</b></col>, <cd>to become separated by
pulling; <as>as, a rope will <ex>pull apart</ex></as>.</cd> --
<col><b>To pull up</b></col>, <cd>to draw the reins; to stop; to
halt.</cd> -- <col><b>To pull through</b></col>, <cd>to come
successfully to the end of a difficult undertaking, a dangerous
sickness, or the like.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pull
<hw>Pull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of pulling or
drawing with force; an effort to move something by drawing toward
one.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I awakened with a violent <qex>pull</qex> upon the ring which was
fastened at the top of my box.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A contest; a struggle; <as>as, a wrestling
<ex>pull</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>Carew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A pluck; loss or violence suffered.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two <qex>pulls</qex> at once;⟦br⟧
His lady banished, and a limb lopped off.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A knob, handle, or lever, etc., by which anything is
pulled; <as>as, a drawer <ex>pull</ex>; a bell
<ex>pull</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The act of rowing; <as>as, a <ex>pull</ex> on the
river</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The act of drinking; <as>as, to take a <ex>pull</ex>
at the beer, or the mug</as>.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>
<rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Something in one's favor in a comparison or a
contest; an advantage; means of influencing; <as>as, in weights the
favorite had the <ex>pull</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>A kind of stroke by which a leg
ball is sent to the off side, or an off ball to the side.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>pull</qex> is not a legitimate stroke, but bad
cricket.</q> <rj><qau>R. A. Proctor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pullail</ent>⟦br⟧
